"1632","",
"1634","This chrysid or ""ruby-tailed wasps is a peri-assessment colonist, with 5 records between 2017 and 2021. As such, there is insufficient data to assess or predict any threats to the species.",
"13","",
"20","Always a very rare bee (the largest of 4 species in the Taeniandrena sub genus recorded for the UK) with 20th Century Records from 1950 – 1990 from only 2 locations. The 1950 record was from Somerset (Moorlinch – exact site unknown) – all other records from 1970 – 1990 were from the grassy bank of an old, abandoned railway line in Wiltshire (Burbage). The record from 1990 showed that the species might cling on in this very restricted area but despite repeated visits to this site and Moorlinch it has never been found since and it has been evaluated as RE.",
"21","Although widespread in Central and Southern Europe this bee – very similar to the common and widespread A. dorsata - has been recorded in GB only 3 times in a twenty-year period (1931-1951) - Berkshire (Aldworth) and Dorset (Witchampton and Badbury Rings). Despite targeted survey effort since, the last record is 1951 (Dorset, Badbury Rings) and thus the species is considered RE.",
"38","The inclusion of this bee on the British list rests on a female in the F. Smith Collection in the University Museum, Oxford. The only documentation carried on the pin is “16.8.”. According to R.C.L. Perkins (1914) the specimen was probably sent to Smith by J.B. Bridgman of Norwich as the pin, mode of setting and label is similar to that of other Andrena species known to have been sent by him to Smith in the period 1875-77. As the presence of this taxon is based on a single specimen, with an unclear label, there is a cloud of uncertainty around the validity of this specimen.",
"39","Although the type of this small, double brooded bee (one of the small, dark, “minutula group” of bees) was collected by Kirby in Barham, East Suffolk (pre-1802), it was recorded only 4 other times, the last of which was in 1930 (West Kent, Eynsford). It has not been recorded since and is evaluated as RE.",
"42","The presence of this species as a UK species is based on a single specimen record from 1939, though it is of dubious origin. As such it has not been evaluated.",
"60","This has always been a very rare bee in the UK and some of the most related species are also generally uncommon. There have been difficulties in identification / verification of some older records – the confirmed records are restricted to 9 locations in Suffolk and Dorset, with the last record being in Dorset (Norden, near Corfe Castle) in 1944. It is localised and scarce in Europe and is evaluated as RE in GB.",
"77","",
"87","The presence of this as a UK species is based entirely on 19th Century records for which collecting localities cannot be ascertained and include at least one misidentification. For this reason, the species has not been evaluated.",
"114","",
"115","",
"136","Only known as British from Barham and Nacton (both in Suffolk) pre-1802, no males were ever recorded so this could have been a very briefly, unestablished vagrant. More recent records from the early part of the 20th Century are known to be misidentifications (including one from Lancashire, 1944, in Manchester Museum) and the current distribution is from Central and Southern Europe to West Asia. It is therefore not evaluated.",
"148","",
"156","",
"157","As a peri-assessment (2021) colonist, with potential synanthropic introduction, the species is not evaluated.",
"158","There is only 1 record of this species – it is highly likely to have been a synanthropic colonist, though - additionally - taxonomic difficulties in the genus cast doubt over the veracity of this one record.",
"162","There are only 2 records of males – pre-1960. There have been no records since that time and there is some doubt over their identification (Richards, 1980). As such the species is not evaluated.",
"166","Only 1 male of this of this species (which is recorded reliably from continental Europe) is recorded from Shropshire, but details of the record (other than it being pre-1976) cannot be traced - with a lack of other records it is not evaluated.",
"168","This species of ant has been recorded only once. According to Crawley (1920) “The type locality is West Didsbury to where it has apparently been imported via the Liverpool harbour with “Butter Beans”. There is doubt over the identification of the species and the genus is restricted to India and the Oriental region. As such it is a historic synanthropic colonist and has not been evaluated.",
"171","",
"184","",
"188","This “Ruby-tailed wasp” has much in common with Chrysis longula, being very sparingly recorded (Devon, Surrey, Kent and Northamptonshire), sharing the same, main eumenine host (the RE Ancistrocerus antilope – with another partial host of the same sub-family, Euodynerus quadrifasciatus considered extremely rare) and being one of only two relatively large species in the genus (in the UK). It was last recorded, with A. antilope, in 1989 (Steven Falk - internal review – location not stated). As it was always v. restricted and seldom found – and has not been found since – it seems reasonable to evaluate as RE.",
"190","Historically, this “Cuckoo” or “Ruby-tailed” wasp – a specific parasite of a eumenine wasp - was very sparingly recorded from Devon to Kent, north to Gloucestershire, Oxfordshire and Suffolk, with an outlying old record from Aberdeenshire. The last record for GB was in 1927 (exact location unknown) and although this is a taxonomically challenging genus, the species is relatively large for the genus, the host (Ancistrocerus antilope) has been evaluated as RE and thus the evaluation of RE is considered appropriate.",
"200","",
"202","",
"209","",
"212","Historically this species was mostly restricted the southeast of England and more so in the twentieth century (East Sussex and Kent). The most recent records were Kent in 1966 (Pluckley) and 1970 (Maplesden). This genus of bees (with notably long antennae) is very distinctive, the species was always scarce, and with no further records, despite targeted surveying in the assessment period, it is evaluated as RE.",
"214","This is frequently an accidentally introduced species of predominantly Mediterranean origin. As a synanthropic colonist the species is not evaluated.",
"215","This tropical or sub-tropical species has been accidentally introduced on numerous occasions and as a synanthropic colonist is not evaluated.",
"218","",
"219","",
"221","",
"224","There are some 19th century records of this distinctive halictid bee, and two thriving nesting aggregations survived in South Devon (Chudleigh) from 1919-1930, but there have been no more recent records and RE is an appropriate evaluation.",
"226","",
"229","",
"230","",
"252","Somewhat curiously, the only record of this species in 1847 was - as with M. ericetorum – from Weybridge in Surrey. With no records before or since it must be strongly suspected as a synanthropic colonist and is not evaluated.",
"256","The 1844 record of this species was of a female and male specimen (Weybridge, Surrey). Other older records have never been authenticated, and it is a species prone to synanthropic colonisation. It is therefore not evaluated.",
"271","",
"289","Significant taxonomic confusion surrounds this genus. It is uncertain whether this species has been correctly identified to modern standards. Potential specimens exist (Mike Edwards collection, pers.comm.) but they require re-identification and confirmation.",
"301","Although present in Continental Europe, this small wasp of the Bethylidae family is regarded as a synanthropic colonist and is therefore not evaluated.",
"307","This ground nesting, fly-hunting wasp has always been the far less common of two species of the genus in the UK historically (and is distinct in colouration from the very common and widespread M. arvensis - having ivory rather than yellow markings), when it was widespread but scarce in England and Wales, the last record of the species was from Yorkshire (Spurn Head) in 1952, and it is thus evaluated RE.",
"313","An early assessment nomenclatural change means there is an imperfect knowledge of the true distribution of this parasitic bee.","Insufficient data were available to reach a supportable conclusion on the threat status for this taxon."
"318","",
"319","",
"320","",
"321","",
"343","Through the timespan of records (1878 – 1982) this has always been a scarce and very restricted parasitic bee (1 small area of coast on the Isle of Purbeck, Dorset). Despite the increasing range of its host species (Andrena nitidiuscula) and a great deal of targeted searching under the Biodiversity Action Plan (~ 1995-2010) it has not been found in the assessment period and is evaluated as RE. Parasitic species often become extinct a long time before a host shows evidence of considerable and serious decline.",
"350","",
"376","",
"421","",
"427","",
"430","As with L. humile, this ant is a synanthropic colonist that originates from South America, though has not been as widely introduced as a non-native species and not as well established beyond its native range. It is thus not evaluated.",
"440","",
"443","",
"444","Following taxonomic revision, there are no defined records of this species, and the taxonomic validity of the species designation is very uncertain. As such, it is not evaluated.",
"456","As this ground nesting eumenine wasp became extinct in the Channel Islands in 1952 it is perhaps unsurprising that the last confirmed mainland (GB) records was from Hampshire (New Forest) 1909. It has been assessed as RE.",
"463","A record of a single female from Sittingbourne in East Kent in 1959, collected by J C Felton, cannot be traced. The species is not evaluated.",
"469","A synanthropic colonist with previous records from Granaries – not assessed.",
"470","A synanthropic colonist with previous records from Warehouses and therefore not assessed.",
"471","In contrast to the two other synanthropic species of its genus recorded in GB, this small, bethylid wasp (thought to be associated with the Cis genus of tree-fungus beetles) can survive outdoors. The is proved by the sole record – from Erme Mouth, South Devon (Hamilton – in Perkins, 1976) from 1970. Bethylid wasps are very poor / weak fliers and vagrancy from mainland Europe to a river valley in a rural area of southwest England does not appear to be plausible – in addition, the other European records of this species are from Fenno-Scandia. This is the only GB record, and it is evaluated as RE.",
"475","This mound building “wood ant” has strong populations on the Channel Islands (out with the geographical scope of this assessment). It is worth noting the taxonomic and identification difficulties associated with the “wood ants” historically and the species been subject to targeted survey effort without being found. Mainland records were only made from two locations – from the Dorset heathland near Wareham and the Bournemouth area where it was discovered in 1864. The last known nest, near Wareham, died out in 1987 leading to an evaluation of RE.",
"484","This species is a synanthropic colonist (it has been imported in cork from Europe) and therefore is not evaluated.",
"492","",
"502","",
"503","A synanthropic colonist with a native range across Southern Europe, North Africa and the Middle East, it is not evaluated.",
"512","As this species is under statutory control as a non-native invasive pest it cannot be assessed or evaluated.",
"514","Following the confirmed peri-assessment nomenclatural change to this species (2018) the biology and ecology of the species may be elucidated at a later date (though the separation of this species from T. caespitum relies on analysis of pheromones at present, which will hamper efforts in the short term).","Insufficient data were available to reach a supportable conclusion on the threat status for this taxon."
"517","Even in in tropical and sub-tropical regions, populations are associated with greenhouses, zoos and heated buildings (Bolton 1980). This synanthropic colonist is not evaluated.",
"518"," This pan-tropical species of African origin (Bolton 1980) is a synanthropic colonist and is thus not evaluated.",
"526","There is a putative record of this from 1832. The eminent Hymenopterist O.W. Richards regarded the record as dubious.",
"527","Old records come from observations noted by F. Smith prior to 1880 around Windsor and Ascot in Berkshire (Falk, 1991). A more recent record is from Oxshott Heath, Surrey, in 1950 (Baker in Baldock, 2010) has not been inspected and there is doubt about the identification. All records (including from 1950 – if correct) are regarded as vagrants and therefore the species is not evaluated.",
"540","No breeding presence has ever been established and there is potential confusion to Bombus lapidarius males (a very common and widespread species). Specimens cannot be found in museum collections. In Benton's New Naturalist 2006, he notes that the dates for these taxa vary according to various sources, being in either 1837, 1863, or 1857. Given the doubt that this species was ever present in GB – or present as an established breeding species – it has not been evaluated.",
"555","Despite the fact there are more difficulties in identifying bumblebee’s than is generally supposed, they are easily the most often recorded bee (and aculeate) of most places where they are present. B. cullumanus was always a rare species – restricted to Southeast England and only recorded from chalk grassland – and is much declined over the whole of Europe. The last record for GB was in 1941 Berkshire (Blewbury) – though the year is uncertain - and it is evaluated as RE.",
"557","The only known record is of a female collected by F Smith at Kingsdown, near Deal, East Kent, in August 1860. This is considered a vagrant from Continental Europe and therefore has not been evaluated.",
"583","",
"585","As well as having taxonomic and identification difficulties in the past (with the latter still relevant), this small halictid bee – specifically associated with Sheep’s-bit Jasione montana for pollen – was confirmed nesting in GB. It was recorded from Surrey (Woking, around 1910, and Byfleet between 1913 and 1920). There are unconfirmed records from Dorset (Ferndown 1948 and Parley 1953). As such, RE seems entirely appropriate.",
"595","The sole British record, the type species of this megachilid bee, was a female taken by Kirby at Coddenham, East Suffolk, prior to 1802, though there is no firm evidence to suggest the species was a vagrant or accidental introduction. Globally, the species is known from France and Spain in the west to China in the east but must be considered RE in a GB context.",
"597","There is considerable doubt over the veracity of the two late 19th Century records for this species and it is not evaluated.",
"598","This eumenine wasp, also known as Ancistrocerus quadratus (Panzer, 1799), has always had a restricted distribution, being found in only 4 counties in the 20th century (Devon, Herefordshire, Leicestershire and Nottinghamshire – with the last record from Devon in 1969). There are no post-1970 records – despite targeted surveys during the 30-year assessment period of the current Red List - and it has been evaluated as RE.",
"606","Always a widespread but rarely recorded species in GB, the last confirmed record of this eumenine wasp pre-dates the current Red-list assessment period (17/06/1989). There is a reported specimen from Greenwich Peninsula Ecology Park from surveys conducted by David Notton for British Museum for Natural History (BMNH; 2016-17 – Steven Falk internal review comment). David Notton passed all Vespidae specimens to Michael Archer for determination, then deposited them in the BNHM collection. The specimen can’t be traced (Gavin Broad, Senior Curator at BNHM, pers. comm. and Jaswinder Boparai, volunteer curator at BNHM pers. comm.). This, combined with targeted, unsuccessful survey effort in other areas during the Red List period, leads to evaluation as RE.",
"607","",
"611","There are only two historic records of the species from Hayling Island, Hampshire (“Hants: Hayling Island, 2, males, 1961, at roots of grass (J. A. J. Clark), 1 male 24.iv.1962 (D. J. Clark)” – Perkins 1976). It was used in biocontrol of pests in stored goods and is regarded as a synanthropic colonist and not evaluated.",
"612","",
"629","As with the majority of bethyloid wasps details of biology and ecology are imperfectly known. This species in particular is subject to a high degree of taxonomic uncertainty. The last record submitted was in 1930.","Insufficient data were available to reach a supportable conclusion on the threat status for this taxon."
"631","As with all bethyloid wasps details of biology and ecology are imperfectly known. This species in particular is subject to a high degree of taxonomic uncertainty. The last record submitted was in 1930.","Insufficient data were available to reach a supportable conclusion on the threat status for this taxon."
"643","This ant’s native range covers tropical areas of the New and Old World. It is widely introduced and is recorded from greenhouses and other heated buildings in temperate areas including Europe. A synanthropic colonist – not evaluated",
"651","In the 19th Century this was a widespread but scarce species in the southeast of England. However, being a parasitic bee reliant on an Endangered host (Anthophora retusa) and with the last record from the South Hampshire (New Forest) in 1912 it is evaluated as RE.",
"653","",
"654","This ant – originally from Africa – has been introduced into many areas globally. There is an 1850 record, though a 2015 determination of a specimen was incorrect. A non-established synanthropic colonist that is not evaluated.",
"655"," Although this species has established in the London area (the first record being from 2016) – it is a Nearctic species and having established in the post-assessment period is thus not evaluated.",
"659","Members of this genus of wasps (Bethylidae) are often used as Bio-control agents for storage pests. It is regarded as a synanthropic colonist and is therefore not evaluated.",
"660","Members of this genus of wasps (Bethylidae) are often used as Bio-control agents for storage pests. It is regarded as a synanthropic colonist and is therefore not evaluated.",
"661","A wasp with records only from Warehouses. A parasite of beetle (Laemophloeus) larvae occurring in stored grain (see Finlayson, 1950). It is regarded as a synanthropic colonist and has not been evaluated.",
"662","The wasp Cephalonomia tarsalis parasitizes larvae of the “saw-toothed grain beetle” Oryzaephilus surinamensis, which feed on wheat grains. With the only records from Warehouses, it is regarded as a synanthropic colonist and has not been evaluated.",
"663","This small wasp, which predates tree fungus beetles of the Cis genus, has only been recorded in Oxford. In 1918 A. Hamm found a female carrying a beetle larvae with 4 eggs eggs - these eggs hatched but no specimens have been found since.",
"664","This wasp – which occurs naturally in tropical regions - is a gregarious external parasitoid of the larvae and pupae of the “cigarette beetle” - Lasioderma serricorne (Coleoptera: Anobiidae) - which itself is an injurious pest to stored dried products, other animals and vegetable materials. All records come from Warehouses. As such it is regarded as a synanthropic colonist and has not been evaluated.",
"666","Although extant in the Channel Islands (out with the geographical scope of this assessment), this large, Spider-hunting wasp has only been recorded twice on the mainland – 2 nearby sites in Dorset in 1934 and 1938 (GM Spooner). With no records since – and given the fact it is not likely to be overlooked on account of its size – it is evaluated as RE.",
"678","Although this wasp of Europe, N. Africa and the Levant is spreading in Europe, the two pre-1900 records from the UK are from a recorder judged to be unreliable and therefore the species is not evaluated.",
"687","This wasp was recorded in 1853 (Weybridge, Surrey) and not seen again until 2022 (London – A. Madgwick – 1 male). An aerial, wood nesting species, it is regarded as a synanthropic colonist and is therefore not evaluated.",
"1611","This species has undergone a post-assessment nomenclatural change and therefore has not been evaluated.",
"1612","This species has undergone a post-assessment nomenclatural change and therefore has not been evaluated.",
"1614","This species has undergone a post-assessment nomenclatural change and, due to possible confusion with similar species in the Taeniandrena sub genus cannot therefore be evaluated.",
"1622","As with many species in this genus, subject to post-assessment nomenclatural change and therefore not evaluated.",
"1624","As with many species in this genus, subject to post-assessment nomenclatural change and therefore not evaluated.",
"1625","The sub-family (Pemphredoninae) which includes this genus is fraught with taxonomic and nomenclatural difficulties. As this is a post-assessment nomenclatural change, the species is not evaluated.",
"1626","As with many species in this genus, subject to post-assessment nomenclatural change and therefore not evaluated.",
"1627","",
"1628","The one GB record for this species is a misidentification (it is the DD – probably vagrant - E. papillarius) and therefore it is not evaluated.",
"1629","Due to post-assessment nomenclatural change this species has not been evaluated.",
"587","This parasitic wasp has been recorded very infrequently. Last known in Herefordshire in 1983, which has been re-checked 2022 and found to be genuine, but identification difficulties and an apparent elusiveness on the part of the wasp hampers any elucidation of biology or ecology.","Insufficient data were available to reach a supportable conclusion on the threat status for this taxon."
"1630","Until the recognition of N. glabella this was regarded as a particularly variable species. Due to that post assessment change in taxonomy, it is not evaluated.",
"1631","Until very recently this taxon was regarded as a colour form of the particularly variable N. panzeri. Following investigation (Falk 2022), it is apparent that N. glabella is morphologically and genetically distinct – with a specific host association - though this post-assessment change means the species is not evaluated.",
"1633","This social wasp is a post-assessment colonist. The most recent data appears that it is establishing on the Kent coast.",
"1635","The only UK record – based on a specimen – is under review and the species is therefore not able to be evaluated at present.",
"1636","A pre-assessment nomenclatural change prevents elucidation of the distribution for this solitary wasp. Material is being examined in collections but not enough specimen material has been re-assessed to elucidate distribution, ecology or biology.","Insufficient data were available to reach a supportable conclusion on the threat status for this taxon."
"1637","This is a post-assessment colonist but given the increasing range of its LC host - Colletes cunicularius: iso. Guichard: 1974 - it is expected that the range of this parasitic bee will be rapid, though without any data to support that at present",
"1640","This ant is of Australasian origin and has thus far only been recorded from Guernsey. As a species restricted to the Channel Islands (and a peri-assessment colonist) it is not evaluated.",
"1641","This species has undergone a post-assessment nomenclatural change and, due to possible confusion with similar species in the Taeniandrena sub genus, cannot therefore be evaluated.",
